# Improvements & TODO Doc Maintenance Rule

## File
`docs/LEO_IMPROVEMENTS_TODO.TODO` – single source of truth for improvements, bugs, refactors, and feature work.

## When to Update

### 1. Completing work that matches an existing item
When your implementation clearly fulfills an existing TODO item (same ID, same scope):
- Set **Status** to `✅ Completed`
- Add **Completed Date** (YYYY-MM-DD)
- Add **Notes** (1–2 lines) describing what was done
- Update the **Summary** table at the top (decrement Pending, increment Completed for that category)
- Update **Last Updated** at the top

### 2. Adding a new tracked improvement
When implementing a user-requested or agreed improvement that should be tracked:
- Add a new entry in the appropriate category (or a suitable existing category) using the same format:
  - `### CAT-ID: Short title`
  - **Status**: ⬜ Pending / 🟡 In Progress / ✅ Completed
  - **Priority**: 🔴 Critical / 🟡 Medium / 🟢 Low
  - **Files**: paths
  - **Issue**: one line
  - **Solution**: one line
  - **Completed Date** / **Notes** if done
- Update the Summary table (Total and category counts)
- Update **Last Updated**

### 3. Change Log (optional but recommended)
When marking an item completed, add a line to the **Change Log** section at the bottom:
`| YYYY-MM-DD | ID | Short description of what was done | AI |`

## Format to Preserve
- Status legend at top: ⬜ Pending | 🟡 In Progress | ✅ Completed | ❌ Cancelled
- Category headers: `## 🎨 Category Name`
- Item IDs: e.g. `UX-VC-001`, `CR-008`, `BUG-003`
- Do not remove or renumber existing items; only add or update status/notes.

## When Not to Update
- Small typo/comment-only changes
- Config or dependency updates with no doc-worthy feature/fix
- If the user says not to touch the TODO doc
